subRequirements.name: Sub-Requirement 1
subRequirements.description:
There are three principal areas of an ECU, where the supplier must apply hardening to the hardware design and implementation:
1. the processing unit chip(s): microprocessors and microcontrollers 
2. memory components that are external to the processing unit(s), such as RAM/ROM, Flash, NVRAM, etc.
3. PCB with discrete elements, interconnections, vias and other components

subRequirements.name: Sub-Requirement 2
subRequirements.description: The supplier must apply hardening to protect against methods that an attacker can use to reverse-engineer, analyze, manipulate or compromise the ECU hardware and the entire system security.

subRequirements.name: Sub-Requirement 3
subRequirements.description: Each processing unit chip must be designed and placed such that its normal behavior (for example boot mode/source, execution/debug mode, reset vector, etc.) cannot be manipulated through physical access to the chip pins.

subRequirements.name: Sub-Requirement 4
subRequirements.description: Each processing unit chip must be designed and placed such that no sensitive data can be extracted from the chip through physical access to the chip pins.

detailedFindings.purpose: Gain access to the system via physical ports
detailedFindings.threat: An attacker with physical access can read memory and debug the processors.
detailedFindings.recommendations: Close JTAG in production level software

detailedFindings.purpose: Gain access to the system via physical ports
detailedFindings.threat: An attacker with physical access can receive a shell on all three VMs.
detailedFindings.recommendations: Close UART in production level software

detailedFindings.purpose: Gain access to the system via Ethernet network
detailedFindings.threat: An attacker with access to the OBD-2 connector can obtain shell access on all three VMs.
detailedFindings.recommendations: Disable SSH in production level software

detailedFindings.purpose: Exploitation of DoIP communication on the Chorus processor
Exploitation of DoIP communication on the Chorus processor
Exploitation of DoIP communication on the VMs of the RCAR processor

detailedFindings.threat: An attacker with ability to send UDS messages to the X processor can flash malicious firmware to the processor and gain persistent code execution.
detailedFindings.recommendations: During reception of FirstFrame, add a check of the payload length against the size of the whole ISO-TP stream.

securityConcepts.name: Security Concepts 1
descriptions: System development must comply with "xxx.x": Secure ECU hardware platform".
Hardware must be hardened and be resilient to physical attack methods such as reverse-engineering, system analysis, manipulating, and compromising hardware or memory buffers.
